Conceptual fix: move FluentValidation from Commands to Request DTOs

  There is a design misalignment in the current validation setup. Validation is currently applied to CQRS Commands (e.g. CreateTodoListCommandValidator, AddTodoItemCommandValidator), but validation should
  happen at the API boundary — on the Request DTOs that controllers receive from HTTP clients.

  Commands are internal objects; they should be trusted by the time they reach the Wolverine pipeline. The Request DTOs are the untrusted, user-facing input.

  What needs to change:

  1. Remove the existing Command validators:
    - Application/Commands/CreateTodoList/CreateTodoListCommandValidator.cs
    - Application/Commands/AddTodoItem/AddTodoItemCommandValidator.cs
    - Any other *CommandValidator files
  2. Create Request validators (mirror the same rules on the corresponding Request DTOs):
    - Controllers/TodoLists/Commands/CreateTodoListRequestValidator.cs → AbstractValidator<CreateTodoListRequest>
    - Controllers/TodoItems/Commands/AddTodoItemRequestValidator.cs → AbstractValidator<AddTodoItemRequest>
    - And equivalents for UpdateTodoListRequest, UpdateTodoItemRequest
  3. Add an ASP.NET Core IAsyncActionFilter as ValidationMiddleware to intercept invalid ModelState before reaching controller logic. Follow this pattern:

  // Infrastructure/Middleware/ValidationMiddleware.cs
  public class ValidationMiddleware : IAsyncActionFilter
  {
      public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next)
      {
          if (!context.ModelState.IsValid)
          {
              var errors = context.ModelState
                  .Where(p => p.Value.Errors.Count > 0)
                  .ToDictionary(k => k.Key, v => v.Value.Errors.Select(e => e.ErrorMessage))
                  .SelectMany(e => e.Value)
                  .Distinct()
                  .Aggregate((a, b) => $"{a}\n{b}");
              throw new ValidationException(errors);
          }
          await next();
      }
  }

  4. Register FluentValidation + the action filter in the DI setup (likely Infrastructure/Configuration/):

  services.AddFluentValidationAutoValidation();
  services.AddFluentValidationClientsideAdapters();
  services.AddValidatorsFromAssembly(typeof(YourAssemblyMarker).Assembly);
  services.AddControllers(options => options.Filters.Add<ValidationMiddleware>());
  services.Configure<ApiBehaviorOptions>(options => options.SuppressModelStateInvalidFilter = true);

  5. Update documentation to reflect that validation is at the HTTP request boundary (Request DTOs), not the application layer (Commands). The Wolverine ValidationMiddleware in Infrastructure/Mediator/ should
  be removed or noted as deprecated.

  Example validator to produce (adapted to project style):

  // Controllers/TodoLists/Commands/CreateTodoListRequestValidator.cs
  public sealed class CreateTodoListRequestValidator : AbstractValidator<CreateTodoListRequest>
  {
      public CreateTodoListRequestValidator()
      {
          RuleFor(x => x.Name)
              .NotEmpty().WithErrorCode("todolists.name.empty")
              .MaximumLength(200).WithErrorCode("todolists.name.too_long");
      }
  }

